The diversion affected mainly Northern states such as Kano, Adamawa, Borno, Kwara, among others. Several domestic flights on Saturday were diverted across the country following bad weather. The diversion affected mainly Northern states such as Kano, Adamawa, Borno, Kwara, among others. Many passengers have been experiencing delays and cancellations as a result of poor visibility caused by the weather since the beginning of this week. As of the time of filing this report, flights from Lagos to Kano had returned due to bad weather, leaving many passengers stranded, and some flights had landed in Abuja, according to Daily Trust. During a visit to the airport around 8:30 a.m., it was announced that the Air Peace flight to Ilorin had been delayed for an additional hour due to weather at the destination airport. Some passengers heading to Ilorin were reportedly routed through Abuja's Nnamdi Azikiwe International Airport (NAIA) in the hope of connecting to Ilorin International Airport from there. One of the passengers' relatives told Daily Trust that he had been waiting at Ilorin Airport since 7:00 a.m. to pick up his brother. The passengers on Air Peace's Lagos-Kano flight were also dropped off in Abuja because the aircraft could not proceed to Mallam Aminu Kano International Airport due to hazy weather in the North West State. Kano flights on Air Peace, Max Air and Azman have experienced cancellations for most parts of this week, with the airlines blaming the development on weather. 